# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ebola-virus
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Such a name is called a **binomial name** (often shortened to just "binomial"), a **binomen**, **binominal name**, or a **scientific name**; more informally, it is also called a **Latin name**.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] In the International Code of Zoological Nomenclature (ICZN), the system is also called **binominal nomenclature**, with an "n" before the "al" in "binominal", which is *not* a typographic error, meaning "two-name naming system".
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] The first part of the name – the *generic name* – identifies the genus to which the species belongs, whereas the second part – the *specific name* or *specific epithet* – distinguishes the species within the genus.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] For example, modern humans belong to the genus *Homo* and within this genus to the species *Homo sapiens*.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] The formal introduction of this system of naming species is credited to Carl Linnaeus, effectively beginning with his work *Species Plantarum* in 1753.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] But as early as 1622, Gaspard Bauhin introduced in his book *Pinax theatri botanici* (English, *Illustrated Exposition of Plants*) containing many names of genera that were later adopted by Linnaeus.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Binomial nomenclature was introduced in order to provide succinct, relatively stable and verifiable names that could be used and understood internationally, unlike common names which are usually different in every language.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Although the general principles underlying binomial nomenclature are common to these two codes, there are some differences in the terminology they use and their particular rules.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] In modern usage, the first letter of the generic name is always capitalized in writing, while that of the specific epithet is not, even when derived from a proper noun such as the name of a person or place.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Similarly, both parts are italicized in normal text (or underlined in handwriting).
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Thus the binomial name of the annual phlox (named after botanist Thomas Drummond) is now written as *Phlox drummondii*.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Often, after a species name is introduced in a text, the generic name is abbreviated to the first letter in subsequent mentions (e.g., *P. drummondii*).
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] In scientific works, the authority for a binomial name is usually given, at least when it is first mentioned, and the year of publication may also be specified.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] The word *binomial* is composed of two elements: *bi-* (Latin prefix meaning 'two') and *nomial* (the adjective form of *nomen*, Latin for 'name').
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] In Medieval Latin, the related word *binomium* was used to signify one term in a binomial expression in mathematics.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] In fact, the Latin word *binomium* may validly refer to either of the epithets in the binomial name, which can equally be referred to as a *binomen* (pl.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Before the adoption of the modern binomial system of naming species, a scientific name consisted of a generic name combined with a specific name that was from one to several words long.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Together they formed a system of polynomial nomenclature.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] These names had two separate functions: to designate or label the species, and to be a diagnosis or description.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] These two goals were eventually found to be incompatible.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Such "polynomial names" may sometimes look like binomials, but are different.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] For example, Gerard's herbal (as amended by Johnson) describes various kinds of spiderwort: "The first is called *Phalangium ramosum*, Branched Spiderwort; the second, *Phalangium non ramosum*, Unbranched Spiderwort.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] The other ... is aptly termed *Phalangium Ephemerum Virginianum*, Soon-Fading Spiderwort of Virginia".
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] The Latin phrases are short descriptions, rather than identifying labels.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] The Bauhins, in particular Caspar Bauhin (1560–1624), took some important steps towards the binomial system by pruning the Latin descriptions, in many cases to two words.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] The adoption by biologists of a system of strictly binomial nomenclature is due to Swedish botanist and physician Carl Linnaeus (1707–1778).
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] It was in his 1753 *Species Plantarum* that Linnaeus began consistently using a one-word **trivial name** (*nomen triviale*) after a generic name (genus name) in a system of binomial nomenclature.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Trivial names had already appeared in his *Critica Botanica* (1737) and *Philosophia Botanica* (1751).
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] This trivial name is what is now known as a specific epithet (*ICNafp*) or specific name (*ICZN*).
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] The Bauhins' genus names were retained in many of these, but the descriptive part was reduced to a single word.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Linnaeus's trivial names introduced the idea that the function of a name could simply be to give a species a unique label, meaning that the name no longer needed to be descriptive.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Both parts could, for example, be derived from the names of people.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Thus Gerard's *Phalangium ephemerum virginianum* became *Tradescantia virginiana*, where the genus name honoured John Tradescant the Younger, an English botanist and gardener.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] A bird in the parrot family was named *Psittacus alexandri*, meaning "Alexander's parrot", after Alexander the Great, whose armies introduced eastern parakeets to Greece.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Linnaeus's trivial names were much easier to remember and use than the parallel polynomial names, and eventually replaced them.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Nowadays, many species are mainly referred to by their binomial names, even in non-specialized fields, such as environmental education and the internet in general.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Because of this use, the binomial *Tyrannosaurus rex* is widely known.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Binomial nomenclature for species has the effect that when a species is moved from one genus to another, sometimes the specific name or epithet must be changed as well.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] This may happen because the specific name is already used in the new genus, or to agree in gender with the new genus if the specific epithet is an adjective modifying the genus name.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Some biologists have argued for the combination of the genus name and specific epithet into a single unambiguous name, or for the use of uninomials (as used in nomenclature of ranks above species).
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Because genus names are unique only within a nomenclature code, it is possible for homonyms (two or more species sharing the same genus name) to happen, and even the same binomial if they occur in different kingdoms.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] At least 1,258 instances of genus name duplication occur (mainly between zoology and botany).
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Nomenclature (including binomial nomenclature) is not the same as classification, although the two are related.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Classification is the ordering of items into groups based on similarities or differences; in biological classification, species are one of the kinds of item to be classified.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] In principle, the names given to species could be completely independent of their classification.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] This is not the case for binomial names, since the first part of a binomial is the name of the genus into which the species is placed.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] The independence is only partial since the names of families and other higher taxa are usually based on genera.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Taxonomy includes both nomenclature and classification.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Its first stages (sometimes called "alpha taxonomy") are concerned with finding, describing and naming species of living or fossil organisms.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Binomial nomenclature is thus an important part of taxonomy as it is the system by which species are named.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Taxonomists are also concerned with classification, including its principles, procedures and rules.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] A complete binomial name is always treated grammatically as if it were a phrase in the Latin language (hence the common use of the term "Latin name" for a binomial name).
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] However, the two parts of a binomial name can each be derived from a number of sources, of which Latin is only one.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] The first part of the name, which identifies the genus, must be a word that can be treated as a Latin singular noun in the nominative case.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] It must be unique within the purview of each nomenclatural code, but can be repeated between them.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Thus *Huia recurvata* is an extinct species of plant, found as fossils in Yunnan, China, whereas *Huia masonii* is a species of frog found in Java, Indonesia.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] The second part of the name, which identifies the species within the genus, is also treated grammatically as a Latin word.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Whereas the first part of a binomial name must be unique within the purview of each nomenclatural code, the second part is quite commonly used in two or more genera (as is shown by examples of *hodgsonii* above), but cannot be used more than once within a single genus.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] The full binomial name must be unique within each code.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] From the early 19th century onwards, it became ever more apparent that a body of rules was necessary to govern scientific names.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] In the course of time these became nomenclature codes.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Virus names are governed by the *International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses* (*ICTV*), a taxonomic code, which determines taxa as well as names.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Unifying the different codes into a single code, the "*BioCode*", has been suggested, although implementation is not in sight.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] (There is also a published code for a different system of biotic nomenclature, which does not use ranks above species, but instead names clades.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] As noted above, there are some differences between the codes in how binomials can be formed; for example the *ICZN* allows both parts to be the same, while the *ICNafp* does not.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Another difference is in how personal names are used in forming specific names or epithets.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] The *ICNafp* sets out precise rules by which a personal name is to be converted to a specific epithet.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] In particular, names ending in a consonant (but not "er") are treated as first being converted into Latin by adding "-ius" (for a man) or "-ia" (for a woman), and then being made genitive (i.e. meaning "of that person or persons").
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] This produces specific epithets like *lecardii* for Lecard (male), *wilsoniae* for Wilson (female), and *brauniarum* for the Braun sisters.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] By contrast, the *ICZN* does not require the intermediate creation of a Latin form of a personal name, allowing the genitive ending to be added directly to the personal name.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] This explains the difference between the names of the plant *Magnolia hodgsonii* and the bird *Anthus hodgsoni*.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Furthermore, the *ICNafp* requires names not published in the form required by the code to be corrected to conform to it, whereas the *ICZN* is more protective of the form used by the original author.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] By tradition, the binomial names of species are usually typeset in italics; for example, *Homo sapiens*.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Generally, the binomial should be printed in a font style different from that used in the normal text; for example, "*Several more*Homo sapiens*fossils were discovered*." When handwritten, a binomial name should be underlined; for example, Homo sapiens.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] The first part of the binomial, the genus name, is always written with an initial capital letter.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Older sources, particularly botanical works published before the 1950s, used a different convention: if the second part of the name was derived from a proper noun, e.g., the name of a person or place, a capital letter was used.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Thus, the modern form *Berberis darwinii* was written as *Berberis Darwinii*.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] A capital was also used when the name is formed by two nouns in apposition, e.g., *Panthera Leo* or *Centaurea Cyanus*.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] In current usage, the second part is never written with an initial capital.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] When used with a common name, the scientific name often follows in parentheses, although this varies with publication.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] The binomial name should generally be written in full.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] For example, a list of members of the genus *Canis* might be written as "*Canis lupus*, *C. aureus*, *C. simensis*".
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] The abbreviation "sp." is used when the actual specific name cannot or need not be specified.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] The abbreviation "spp." (standing for *species pluralis*, Latin for "multiple species") indicates "several species".
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] These abbreviations are not italicised (or underlined).
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] For example: "*Canis* sp." means "an unspecified species of the genus *Canis*", while "*Canis* spp." means "two or more species of the genus *Canis*".
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] (These abbreviations should not be confused with the abbreviations "ssp." (zoology) or "subsp." (botany), plurals "sspp." or "subspp.", referring to one or more subspecies.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] The abbreviation "cf." (i.e., *confer* in Latin) is used to compare individuals/taxa with known/described species.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Conventions for use of the "cf." qualifier vary.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] In paleontology, it is typically used when the identification is not confirmed.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] *nasicus*" was used to indicate "a fossil bird similar to the Cuban crow but not certainly identified as this species".
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] In molecular systematics papers, "cf." may be used to indicate one or more undescribed species assumed to be related to a described species.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] *spectabile*" because they had been viewed as related to, but distinct from, *Etheostoma spectabile* (orangethroat darter).
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] This view was supported to varying degrees by DNA analysis.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] The somewhat informal use of taxa names with qualifying abbreviations is referred to as open nomenclature and it is not subject to strict usage codes.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] In some contexts, the dagger symbol ("†") may be used before or after the binomial name to indicate that the species is extinct.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] In scholarly texts, at least the first or main use of the binomial name is usually followed by the "authority" – a way of designating the scientist(s) who first published the name.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] The authority is written in slightly different ways in zoology and botany.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] For names governed by the *ICZN* the surname is usually written in full together with the date (normally only the year) of publication.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] The International Plant Names Index maintains an approved list of botanical author abbreviations.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Historically, abbreviations were used in zoology too.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] When the original name is changed, e.g., the species is moved to a different genus, both codes use parentheses around the original authority; the *ICNafp* also requires the person who made the change to be given.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] In the *ICNafp*, the original name is then called the basionym.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Binomial nomenclature, as described here, is a system for naming species.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Implicitly, it includes a system for naming genera, since the first part of the name of the species is a genus name.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] In a classification system based on ranks, there are also ways of naming ranks above the level of genus and below the level of species.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Ranks above genus (e.g., family, order, class) receive one-part names, which are conventionally not written in italics.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Thus, the house sparrow, *Passer domesticus*, belongs to the family Passeridae.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Family names are normally based on genus names, such as in zoology, although the endings used differ between zoology and botany.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Ranks below species receive three-part names, conventionally written in italics like the names of species.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] There are significant differences between the *ICZN* and the *ICNafp*.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] In zoology, the only formal rank below species is subspecies and the name is written simply as three parts (a trinomen).
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Thus, one of the subspecies of the olive-backed pipit is *Anthus hodgsoni berezowskii*.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Informally, in some circumstances, a form may be appended, though such names are unavailable, and have no formal standing in zoological nomenclature (i.e., they have no recognized author or date, and do not compete for homonymy).
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] *spectabilis* is the harlequin ladybird in its black or melanic forms having four large orange or red spots.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] In botany, there are many ranks below species and although the name itself is written in three parts, a "connecting term" (not part of the name) is needed to show the rank.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] Thus, the American black elder is *Sambucus nigra* subsp.
[src:ebola-virus/binomial-name] *canadensis*; the white-flowered form of the ivy-leaved cyclamen is *Cyclamen hederifolium* f.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] Ebola virus and its genus were both originally named for Zaire (now the Democratic Republic of the Congo), the country where it was first described, and was at first suspected to be a new "strain" of the closely related Marburg virus.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] The virus was renamed "Ebola virus" in 2010 to avoid confusion.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] Ebola virus is the single member of the species *Zaire ebolavirus*, which is assigned to the genus *Ebolavirus*, family *Filoviridae*, order *Mononegavirales*.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] The members of the species are called Zaire ebolaviruses.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] The natural reservoir of Ebola virus is believed to be bats, particularly fruit bats, and it is primarily transmitted between humans and from animals to humans through body fluids.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] The EBOV genome is a single-stranded RNA, approximately 19,000 nucleotides long.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] It encodes seven structural proteins: nucleoprotein (NP), polymerase cofactor (VP35), (VP40), GP, transcription activator (VP30), VP24, and RNA-dependent RNA polymerase (L).
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] EBOV carries a negative-sense RNA genome in virions that are cylindrical/tubular, and contain viral envelope, matrix, and nucleocapsid components.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] The overall cylinders are generally approximately 80 nm in diameter, and have a virally encoded glycoprotein (GP) projecting as 7–10 nm long spikes from its lipid bilayer surface.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] The cylinders are of variable length, typically 800 nm, but sometimes up to 1000 nm long.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] The outer viral envelope of the virion is derived by budding from domains of host cell membrane into which the GP spikes have been inserted during their biosynthesis.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] Individual GP molecules appear with spacings of about 10 nm.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] Viral proteins VP40 and VP24 are located between the envelope and the nucleocapsid (see following), in the *matrix space*.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] Each virion contains one molecule of linear, single-stranded, negative-sense RNA, 18,959 to 18,961 nucleotides in length.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] The 3′ terminus is not polyadenylated and the 5′ end is not capped.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] This viral genome codes for seven structural proteins and one non-structural protein.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] The gene order is 3′ – leader – NP – VP35 – VP40 – GP/sGP – VP30 – VP24 – L – trailer – 5′; with the leader and trailer being non-transcribed regions, which carry important signals to control transcription, replication, and packaging of the viral genomes into new virions.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] Sections of the NP, VP35 and the L genes from filoviruses have been identified as endogenous in the genomes of several groups of small mammals.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] It was found that 472 nucleotides from the 3' end and 731 nucleotides from the 5' end are sufficient for replication of a viral "minigenome".
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] Virus sequencing from 78 patients with confirmed Ebola virus disease, representing more than 70% of cases diagnosed in Sierra Leone from late May to mid-June 2014, provided evidence that the 2014 outbreak was no longer being fed by new contacts with its natural reservoir.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] Using third-generation sequencing technology, investigators were able to sequence samples as quickly as 48 hours.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] Like other RNA viruses, Ebola virus mutates rapidly, both within a person during the progression of disease and in the reservoir among the local human population.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] The observed mutation rate of 2.0 × 10−3 substitutions per site per year is as fast as that of seasonal influenza.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] There are two candidates for host cell entry proteins.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] The first is a cholesterol transporter protein, the host-encoded Niemann–Pick C1 (NPC1), which appears to be essential for entry of Ebola virions into the host cell and for its ultimate replication.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] In one study, mice with one copy of the NPC1 gene removed showed an 80 percent survival rate fifteen days after exposure to mouse-adapted Ebola virus, while only 10 percent of unmodified mice survived this long.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] In another study, small molecules were shown to inhibit Ebola virus infection by preventing viral envelope glycoprotein (GP) from binding to NPC1.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] Hence, NPC1 was shown to be critical to entry of this filovirus, because it mediates infection by binding directly to viral GP.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] The same studies described similar results regarding NPC1's role in virus entry for Marburg virus, a related filovirus.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] A further study has also presented evidence that NPC1 is the critical receptor mediating Ebola infection via its direct binding to the viral GP, and that it is the second "lysosomal" domain of NPC1 that mediates this binding.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] TIM-1 was shown to bind to the receptor binding domain of the EBOV glycoprotein, to increase the receptivity of Vero cells.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] Silencing its effect with siRNA prevented infection of Vero cells.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] TIM1 is expressed in tissues known to be seriously impacted by EBOV lysis (trachea, cornea, and conjunctiva).
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] A monoclonal antibody against the IgV domain of TIM-1, ARD5, blocked EBOV binding and infection.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] Together, these studies suggest NPC1 and TIM-1 may be potential therapeutic targets for an Ebola anti-viral drug and as a basis for a rapid field diagnostic assay.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] Being acellular, viruses such as Ebola do not replicate through any type of cell division; rather, they use a combination of host- and virally encoded enzymes, alongside host cell structures, to produce multiple copies of themselves.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] These then self-assemble into viral macromolecular structures in the host cell.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] The virus completes a set of steps when infecting each individual cell.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] The virus begins its attack by attaching to host receptors through the glycoprotein (GP) surface peplomer and is endocytosed into macropinosomes in the host cell.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] To penetrate the cell, the viral membrane fuses with vesicle membrane, and the nucleocapsid is released into the cytoplasm.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] Encapsidated, negative-sense genomic ssRNA is used as a template for the synthesis of polyadenylated, monocistronic mRNAs and, using the host cell's ribosomes, tRNA molecules, etc., the mRNA is translated into individual viral proteins.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] These viral proteins are processed: a glycoprotein precursor (GP0) is cleaved to GP1 and GP2, which are then heavily glycosylated using cellular enzymes and substrates.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] These two molecules assemble, first into heterodimers, and then into trimers to give the surface peplomers.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] Secreted glycoprotein (sGP) precursor is cleaved to sGP and delta peptide, both of which are released from the cell.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] As viral protein levels rise, a switch occurs from translation to replication.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] Using the negative-sense genomic RNA as a template, a complementary +ssRNA is synthesized; this is then used as a template for the synthesis of new genomic (-)ssRNA, which is rapidly encapsidated.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] The newly formed nucleocapsids and envelope proteins associate at the host cell's plasma membrane; budding occurs, destroying the cell.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] Intermediary hosts have been reported to be "various species of fruit bats ... throughout central and sub-Saharan Africa".
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] Evidence of infection in bats has been detected through molecular and serologic means.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] However, ebolaviruses have not been isolated in bats.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] End hosts are humans and great apes, infected through bat contact or through other end hosts.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] Pigs in the Philippines have been reported to be infected with Reston virus, so other interim or amplifying hosts may exist.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] Ebola virus outbreaks tend to occur when temperatures are lower and humidity is higher than usual for Africa.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] Even after a person recovers from the acute phase of the disease, Ebola virus survives for months in certain organs such as the eyes and testes.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] Zaire ebolavirus is one of the four ebolaviruses known to cause disease in humans.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] It has the highest case-fatality rate of these ebolaviruses, averaging 83 percent since the first outbreaks in 1976, although a fatality rate of up to 90 percent was recorded in one outbreak in the Republic of the Congo between December 2002 and April 2003.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] There have also been more outbreaks of Zaire ebolavirus than of any other ebolavirus.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] The first outbreak occurred on 26 August 1976 in Yambuku.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] The first recorded case was Mabalo Lokela, a 44‑year-old schoolteacher.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] The symptoms resembled malaria, and subsequent patients received quinine.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] Transmission has been attributed to reuse of unsterilized needles and close personal contact, body fluids and places where the person has touched.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] The Ebola outbreak that began in March 2014 reached epidemic proportions and killed more than 11,000 people.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] This outbreak was centered in West Africa, an area that had not previously been affected by the disease.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] The toll was particularly grave in three countries: Guinea, Liberia, and Sierra Leone.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] A few cases were also reported in countries outside of West Africa, all related to international travelers who were exposed in the most affected regions and later showed symptoms of Ebola fever after reaching their destinations.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] The severity of the disease in humans varies widely, from rapid fatality to mild illness or even asymptomatic response.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] Studies of outbreaks in the late twentieth century failed to find a correlation between the disease severity and the genetic nature of the virus.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] Hence the variability in the severity of illness was suspected to correlate with genetic differences in the victims.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] This has been difficult to study in animal models that respond to the virus with hemorrhagic fever in a similar manner as humans, because typical mouse models do not so respond, and the required large numbers of appropriate test subjects are not easily available.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] In late October 2014, a publication reported a study of the response to a mouse-adapted strain of Zaire ebolavirus presented by a genetically diverse population of mice that was bred to have a range of responses to the virus that includes fatality from hemorrhagic fever.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] In December 2016, a study found the VSV-EBOV vaccine to be 70–100% effective against the Zaire ebola virus (not the Sudan ebolavirus), making it the first vaccine against the disease.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] Food and Drug Administration in December 2019.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] Ebola virus was first identified as a possible new "strain" of Marburg virus in 1976.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] The International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses (ICTV) identifies Ebola virus as species *Zaire ebolavirus*, which is part of the genus *Ebolavirus*, family *Filoviridae*, order *Mononegavirales*.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] The name "Ebola virus" is derived from the Ebola River—a river that was at first thought to be in close proximity to the area in Democratic Republic of Congo, previously called Zaire, where the 1976 Zaire Ebola virus outbreak occurred—and the taxonomic suffix *virus*.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] In 1998, the virus name was changed to "Zaire Ebola virus" and in 2002 to species *Zaire ebolavirus*.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] However, most scientific articles continued to refer to "Ebola virus" or used the terms "Ebola virus" and "*Zaire ebolavirus*" in parallel.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] Consequently, in 2010, a group of researchers recommended that the name "Ebola virus" be adopted for a subclassification within the species *Zaire ebolavirus*, with the corresponding abbreviation EBOV.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] Previous abbreviations for the virus were EBOV-Z (for "Ebola virus Zaire") and ZEBOV (for "Zaire Ebola virus" or "*Zaire ebolavirus*").
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] In 2011, the ICTV explicitly rejected a proposal (2010.010bV) to recognize this name, as ICTV does not designate names for subtypes, variants, strains, or other subspecies level groupings.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] At present, ICTV does not officially recognize "Ebola virus" as a taxonomic rank, but rather continues to use and recommend only the species designation *Zaire ebolavirus*.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] The prototype Ebola virus, variant Mayinga (EBOV/May), was named for Mayinga N'Seka, a nurse who died during the 1976 Zaire outbreak.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] According to the rules for taxon naming established by the International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses (ICTV), the name *Zaire ebolavirus* is always to be capitalized, italicized, and to be preceded by the word "species".
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] The names of its members (Zaire ebolaviruses) are to be capitalized, are not italicized, and used without articles.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] A recombination event between *Zaire ebolavirus* lineages likely took place between 1996 and 2001 in wild apes giving rise to recombinant progeny viruses.
[src:ebola-virus/ebola-virus] These recombinant viruses appear to have been responsible for a series of outbreaks among humans in Central Africa in 2001–2003.
